🔵 1️⃣ Number vs Number
Example 
console.log(5 > 3);   // true
console.log(5 < 3);   // false
console.log(5 >= 5);  // true
console.log(5 <= 4);  // false


🟡 2️⃣ String vs Number
Rule:
👉 JS string ko number me convert karta hai (agar possible ho)
Example 
console.log("5" > 3);   // true  (5 > 3)
console.log("5" < 10);  // true  (5 < 10)
console.log("10" > 5);  // true

Agar string number jaisi nahi ho:
console.log("abc" > 5); // false (NaN > 5 → false)// important


🔴 4️⃣ == vs === (Most Important)


== (Loose Equality)

👉 Value check karta hai
👉 Type ignore karta hai

console.log(5 == "5");   // true
console.log(true == 1);  // true

=== (Strict Equality)

👉 Value + Type dono check karta hai

console.log(5 === "5");  // false
console.log(true === 1); // false



🟠 5️⃣ Not Equal
checks if 2 value are not equeal 
console.log(5 != 3);     // true
console.log(5 != "5");   // false (type ignore)
console.log(5 != 5);          // false   (same value)
console.log(5 != "5");        // false   ("5" ko 5 bana diya → same)
console.log(5 != 6);          // true    (alag value)
console.log(0 != false);      // false   (false ko 0 bana diya)
console.log("" != 0);         // false   (empty string ko 0 bana diya)
console.log(null != undefined); // false (JS mein null aur undefined loose mein equal maante hain)






🟤 6️⃣ Strict Not Equal
🔴 !== (Strict Not Equal)

👉 Value + Type dono check karta hai
👉 Type convert nahi karta

Example:
console.log(5 !== "5");  // true


Kyuki:

Value same

Type different
console.log(5 !== "5");  // true

🎯 Super Important Rules

> < me string number ban sakti hai

Dono string ho to dictionary compare

== dangerous hai

=== safe hai

🔥 Final Quick Example (Mixed)
console.log("10" > 2);    // true
console.log("2" > "10");  // true
console.log(2 > "10");    // false
console.log(5 == "5");    // true
console.log(5 === "5");   // false


